{"meta": {"institute": "cnrm", "createDate": "2021-09-26 14:00:06.784661", "project": "cordexp", "source": "spreadsheet", "version": 1, "type": "cim.2.science.Model", "id": "f9dfcf3e-0d6c-4f63-a0cb-9f5801eb0d6f"}, "realms": [{"processes": [{"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.dynamical_core", "properties": [{"values": ["Two-time-level semi-lagrangian semi-implicit scheme"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.dynamical_core.name"}, {"values": ["The time discretization is based on a two-time-level semi-Lagrangian semi-implicit numerical integration scheme (e.g., C\u00f4t\u00e9 & Staniforth, 1988). The non-linear terms appearing in the right-hand side of the primitive equations are averaged along the trajectory using their interpolation at the trajectory mid- and departure points. The scheme uses 32-point quasi-cubic interpolations (linear interpolation along the edges of the stencil, fully cubic in the interior \u2013 see Ritchie et al., 1995). Interpolation are also quasi-monotone for all model advected variables (Bermejo & Staniforth, 1992), except the vertical interpolations involved in the momentum and thermodynamic equations. The semi-Lagrangian dynamical core is not fully conservative (e.g., Lucarini & Ragone, 2011). A regional and uniform conservation procedure (mass fixer) is applied for the model atmosphere dry mass (additive correction on the surface pressure): every day, the RCM atmosphere dry mass is forced to be the same as the GCM atmosphere dry mass over the central + relaxation zone. "], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.dynamical_core.overview"}, {"values": ["semi-implicit"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.dynamical_core.timestepping_type"}, {"values": ["divergence/curl", "surface pressure", "temperature"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.dynamical_core.prognostic_variables"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation", "properties": [{"values": ["RRTMG for the longwave and Fouquart-Morcrette for the shortwave"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.name"}, {"values": ["The longwave radiation scheme is based on the version of the Rapid Radiation Transfer Model (RRTM, Mlawer et al. 1997) optimized for GCM, and included in the cycle 37 of the ARPEGE/IFS system (very close to that in the cycle 32, Morcrette et al.). The RRTM scheme follows the two-stream approach and computes upward and downward radiative fluxes in 16 spectral bands encompassing the 10-3000 cm-1 range. The parameterization uses the correlated-k approach with 140 g-points (the number per spectral band depends on the absorption coefficient variations within this band and on the spectral band contribution to the total flux). It includes line absorption by H2O, CO2 , O3 , CH4 , N2O, CFC-11, CFC-12 and CCl4 based on the HITRAN 1996 spectrocospic data base (Rothman et al., 1998) and on the CKD 2.2 water vapor continuum model (Clough et al. 1989). The shortwave radiation scheme, originally developed by Fouquart and Bonnel (1980) and which further evolved in the IFS system until its cycle 32r2 (Morcrette et al., 2008), integrates the fluxes over the whole shortwave spectrum between 200 and 4000 nm. The scheme includes Rayleigh scattering, absorption by water vapor and ozone, both varying in space and time, and by CO2, N2O, CO, CH4 and O2, which are treated as uniformly mixed gases. The parameterization resolved the radiative transfer equations in 6 spectral bands, three bands being in the UV and visible spectral range (185-250, 250-440 and 440-690 nm) and three bands covering the near infrared range (690-1190, 1190-2380 and 2380-4000 nm)."], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.overview"}, {"values": ["Other: volcanic aerosols in the stratosphere, based on the Ammann dataset", "BC: black carbon / soot", "dust", "organic", "sea salt", "sulphate", "Other: The available aerosol species depend on the driving GCMs (see toplevel  info)"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.aerosols"}], "subTopics": [{"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_radiation", "properties": [{"values": ["Fouquart-Morcrette (IFS cycle 32r2)"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_radiation.name"}, {"values": ["wide-band model"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_radiation.spectral_integration"}, {"values": ["two-stream"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_radiation.transport_calculation"}, {"values": ["6.0"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_radiation.spectral_intervals"}, {"values": ["scattering", "emission/absorption,"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_radiation.general_interactions"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_GHG", "properties": [{"values": ["H2O", "CO2: Carbon Dioxide", "O3", "Other: O3 is specified by a climatological monthly file interpolated onto model levels from a climatology coming from University ofReading and calculated by Li and Shine (1995)."], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_GHG.greenhouse_gas_complexity"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.radiation.shortwave_cloud_ice", "properties": [{"values": ["ice water pa